<font color="#FF0000">WANNABES</font><br>
<tt>Sat Apr 19  0:11:20 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I don't know if I CAN feel sorry for or forgive wannabes.<br>
I just feel that they are trying to take away one of the FEW things I have left from that part of my life. My pride of<br>
being a Vietvet. I was no hero. I didn't earn the Bronze<br>
Star or the even fire my weapon that much to defend myself.<br>
I was an Air Force radio maintenence tech at a radar site,<br>
in the middle of an Army helicopter outfit. But I was there<br>
and I did my job and I don't want some wannabe taking that away from me by claiming he was something he wasn't. Sorry,<br>
but thats just how I feel. No one but my family and other<br>
Vets would even acknowledge me when I came home. But now that the civilians and the government say that we are a healed nation in respect to Vietnam, the wannabes come out of the woodwork. How many Vietvets say they are healed? Not all of them by a long shot. The suicide rate among us is to high to say that we are. Maybe I have a lot of healing to <br>
do myself, I kon't know, but don't let a wannabe around me<br>
and start running off at the mouth. I've had that happen and<br>
when the kid found out that I was a Vet, I never again heard<br>
of him bragging that he was taught how to kill someone thirty different ways with his hands. And the good thing was<br>
I didn't have to say a word to him or touch him. (As much<br>
as I wanted to.) Now that I have that out, I guess my e-mail<br>
will be flooded with criticism and advice about see a<br>
counselor. Oh well,..I can handle that better than a wannabe!!!
